A little ditty,

in response to a little ditty

For my friend Wang Ping @wangping9.

The sun arches itself back up

I nurse an aching shoulder by spending the morning splitting wood

Light returns when it is ready, as the pain will leave when my work is done

-B. Randall

Dec. 21st 2022

Two poems, two friends on a rainy day, 

one place.

The first poem is my own, the second is by Wang Ping @wangping9

"Smooth Rock Shot"

1/3/23

"What Makes You Think This is a Poem"

1/10/2023

(For my teacher)
"Note to self, you probably think this poem is about you"

"Uninvited guests"

Photo by Christian Petersen

Spring comes in waves

 breaking a trail through winter

till that music returns

Frogs by the pond begin calling

 Raven clicks to it's mate

Woodpecker drums on a hollow Black Oak

Cricket and cicacda carcass scatter the meadow

 Blue Heron fishes,

 blue gill suspended in icy water
 
 nearly motionless

Are they dreaming of warmth?

Myself exhausted from the work of a day

 out of my own way 

enough to catch sight of that last glimmer

of the sun through the pines at dusk

Brush piles burning along the slopes

 snaking down towards Little Shady Creek

 wind whips the flames

 a large storm approaches

 cranes singing

reminding, there is light just beyond the clouds

that you begin where I end

our bodies move together 

then apart, in waves

"Poetic Crossings, Past & Present: San Juan Ridge

This event honors our rich past and present ridge

poetic tradition, with a night of history, remembering

those who have gone, who we love...... reading selected

works by poets who either once called this place home

or helped to shape the culture during their time here.

Each poet will share a bit of history about the poet they

are reading, a few poems by the featured poet, and a

couple of their own.

Featured Poets and the poets they are celebrating:

Laura Pendell (Dale Pendell)

Will Staple (Allen Ginsberg)

Jacquie Bellon (Her own work and history)

Jamie Hunyor (Gary Snyder)

Susan Suntree (Her own work and history)

Louis Bluecloud (Peter Bluecloud)

Sarah Sparks (Steve Sanfeild)

Davis Reeves (Nanoa Sakaki)

Bishop Randall (Lew Welch)

Doors 6:00. Reading 7:00 PM

$15 suggested donation. Proceeds benefit the

Schoolhouse & Nevada County Arts Council/Sierra Poetry Festival"

Typing along to a chorus of singing birds, pileated woodpecker calls from the east 

an apple tree long given up on, covered in white blossoms, framed by the window facing west

listening, feeling, looking, smelling, tasting 

sitting here in this cabin, sipping coffee that was grown thousands of miles away

B. Randall

4/26/23
Torch spots are full.. A few observer spots remain. Hope you can join us🌱

"Entropy"

Out of work

I piece together what others leave behind

sweater I knit that kept me cool in summer

coming apart due to lack of use

  Fibers themselves do protest

  This seditary leaning by lantern light

  reading of tomorrows news

  The elbow wears on through

B. Randall
5/6/23

The grass so tall

cows from far off

appear as monotone boats

sailing a sea of green

Labels put upon
 
when assuming hurt for hate 

clumsyness learning a heart 

can anything be other than such?

"Who gives a shit, who pays attention
 who doesnt"

Gochisousama deshita,
 that was delicious

"Deer walks slowly
eyes fixed

—having narrowly escaped 
Mountain lion’s jaw

Begins to quiver 
hop quickly

Shaking and moving 
its body in relief
in release

Trauma is natural 
Healing is natural
Both  required

So be wounded 
Sing a song, 
Dance"

Does "art" exist?

 In an anthropological sense, what we term "art" traditional was ceremony. Art seems like a red herring, a distraction from the action itself, our inherit ability to heal ourselves through ancient forms incorporating song, dance, entheogens and picture making..... that have increasingly grown unnecessarily complex, been co-opted, or completely lost. Why is art so difficult to define and name, could it be because it does not exist? We as pipe makes,  craft a tool for carrying fire, for honoring the life giving flame, that hearth we are born to, venture from, then return in ever widening spirals.

Pressure to be original does indeed occur in all aspects of this culture, to foster new, and claim progress even in failure. The hubris of false discovery, while colonizing what was already whole.
Bishop Randall is a North American poet and glass artist.  Currently living in the Yuba watershed, just above the south fork of the Yuba river
